There's a lot of features compacted into this little alarm: On-Off switch, mechanical limit switch for detection, LED light indicators, piezo alarm, as well as teflon tubing for smooth passing of filament through the mechanism. 3) Insert LEDs

description.text:
Not sure what made me decide to actually create this, but I went ahead and did it anyway.  This is a birdhouse designed to look like a traffic light.  Each light can be printed individually, and the faces snap into the housings.  So you can print out 3 faces in different colors and 3 housings and attach them together using either the printable links provided or s-hooks if you have them available.  Or you can screw them into a post or tree using #10 wood screws.  The houses have 3 holes on the sides for ventilation and a hole in the bottom for drainage of water.  No perch because they are dangerous for most songbirds that would use the house (predatorial birds would land on it to snatch the eggs or chicks)  
I also designed a small housing that can hold an LED and a CR2032 battery to light up the face.  The LED housing snaps into the face.  The face is thinned out there to let the light shine through and the LED housing is extra thick to prevent the light from entering the house.  You don't need to print that part if you don't plan on using it.  
Let me know what you think and thanks for reading!

description.text: badBrick 40 Tooth Gear Bearing. Lego Technic compatible. If you don't have a 3D printer but you're interested in getting one of these we can print you one at http://www.badbrick.com/catalog Enjoy.

In MakerWare, I modify the "Medium" settings:
Quality: Layer Height = 0.18 All other defaults are the same. To Assemble: Lay the flat cover with center shaft face up and put the gear over it. Then load it with about 8 balls. Spin the gear some to get them seated. Then carefully pick up the gear by its shaft and hold it together by hand. Push another 5 ball bearings in the gear. Keep some back pressure on it so the center shaft and other balls pop out the other side. The gear will take 13 ball bearings. To make the balls: Print 13 balls. 5.96mm in diameter. Get 2 pieces of 10,000 grit sand paper and lay one on a hard surface. Put the balls on it. Get and another piece, put it on top of them. Get a heavy book, put it on top of the sand paper and rub it around to sand em smooth. Then turn on a frying pan warm it up, and put the balls in there to really polish them up. At this point your wife will start yelling at you... Turn it all off. Put every thing away. Go to the sports store and get a bag of Airsoft 6mm bb's and use them for the bearings. ;-)

title: Choke Tube for Tanked Cox .049 Engines

description.text: This is an experimental choke tube and choke tube mounting plate for tanked .049 Cox engines,. I designed this off of a Cox Babe Bee engine. The point of this is to allow you to have a choke tube on your tanked Cox .049 engine, allowing you to shut off the engine or add a throttle. This is a test peice currently and after testing it I will make changes if needed and post the final version.

First remove the 4 screws on the back of your engine. Next, leaving all of the engine's parts just as they were, place the choke tube plate against the tank backplate with the ridge facing the tank backplate (in the air intake grove). After that insert the screws back through the screw hole, holding on the choke tube plate. description.text:
This is something I made to keep my desk cleaner and more organized. Too often, I have miss-placed my current glue stick or lost the others that came in the same pack. I also find myself diving for my scraper or brush at the last minute before a print starts, to remove a wild strand of filament or something else that has gone wrong. This part utilizes the half size extruded aluminum clamp part I used for my LEDs on my towers. I have been looking for a 'utility' tray that would address my needs without requiring more holes or hardware in my Rostock Max V2. The result is a 3 glue-stick holder (I used the Elmer's disappearing purple sticks to get measurements) with a slot for the SEEMECNC scraper that came with the Rostock Max and one pocket for a sweet (and cheap) brush I found at ACE Hardware. Use it if you need it, mod if it you want to, just be sure to give credit where credit is due. Props to the guy that CADDed the extruded tub clam I used. Remix included. NOTE
Two STLs are included.
1 holds JUST the 3 glue sticks, the other is slightly wider and includes a slot for brush and scraper. EDIT
Added new STL that holds 3 glue sticks (or whatever you want to shove in there) 2 brushes and two scrapers. I use a brass and a nylon brush for the hot end and bed and i realized that depending on what tower you put this thing on, the scraper might not be as easy to get to. This 2x holder is a bit bigger and might be more useful depending on what you want to put in it. I have one on each tower :D great for holding my small trimmers and a small screwdriver. the glue stick hole is also PERFECT for holding my small "tactical" LED flashlight I got at the dollar store.
